Why does ISIS continue to persist?
New York – The deadly terrorist attacks in Istanbul, Dhaka, and Baghdad indicate that ISIS's reach has extended to Europe, North Africa, the Middle East, and Asia-Pacific.
The longer ISIS remains strong in Syria and Iraq, the longer its terrorist network will be able to orchestrate such massacres.
But ISIS is not particularly difficult to eradicate.
The problem lies in the fact that none of the countries involved in Iraq and Syria, including the United States and its allies, regard ISIS as the primary enemy.
This point should have changed.
ISIS has a small fighting force, with the US estimating that it numbers between 20,000 and 25,000 in Iraq and Syria, and around 5,000 in Libya.
Compared to the active military personnel in Syria (125,000), Iraq (271,500), Saudi Arabia (233,500), Turkey (510,600), and Iran (523,000), ISIS is hardly worth mentioning.
In September 2014, U.S. President Barack Obama pledged to "degrade and ultimately destroy" ISIS, but the United States and its allies, including Saudi Arabia, Turkey, and Israel (behind the scenes), have focused instead on undermining Syrian President Bashar al-Assad.
Recently, Israeli Army Brigadier General Herzi Halevi bluntly stated (as relayed to me by a journalist present at a Halevi speech) that "Israel does not want to see the situation in Syria where ISIS is defeated and the superpowers exit the region, and where Hezbollah and Iran, with enhanced strength, face Israel."
Israel opposes ISIS, but its greater concern is Iran backing Assad.
Assad allowed Iran to support Israel's two main quasi-military rivals: Hezbollah and Hamas.
Therefore, Israel's focus is on overthrowing Assad rather than defeating ISIS.
Under the influence of neoconservatism, for the United States, the war in Syria is a continuation of the global hegemonic plan of a US-dominated world that Secretary of Defense Donald Rumsfeld and Deputy Secretary of State Paul Wolfowitz proposed at the end of the Cold War. Note: In the original sentence, "国防部长切尼" was translated as "Defense Secretary Cheney," which refers to Donald Rumsfeld, who held both the position of Defense Secretary and served as Deputy Secretary of State under President Gerald Ford before becoming the Defense Secretary during the George H.W. Bush administration. If Richard Cheney (George W. Bush's Vice President) is intended, the sentence should be adjusted accordingly.
In 1991, Wolfowitz told U.S. General Wesley Clark:
"But we did learn one thing from the Gulf War: that we could use force in that region – in the Middle East – and the Soviets wouldn't stop us."
Before the next superpower emerges to challenge us, we have about 5 to 10 years to clean up the old Soviet client states—Syria, Iran (as originally stated), Iraq.
The U.S. wars in multiple theaters in the Middle East—Afghanistan, Iraq, Syria, Libya, and so on—were aimed at dislodging the Soviet Union and, subsequently, Russia from the competition, allowing the United States to establish its hegemony.
These "efforts" met with a dismal failure.
For Saudi Arabia, and for Israel, the primary goal is to topple Assad to weaken Iran.
Syria is part of the vast proxy war between Shia Iran and Sunni Saudi Arabia, which plays out on battlefields in countries like Syria and Yemen, and along the front lines of more intense Shia-Sunni confrontations in split-prone states such as Bahrain and others in the region, including Saudi Arabia itself.
For Turkey, overthrowing Assad would strengthen its regional position.
But now Turkey faces three adversaries along its southern borders: Assad, ISIS, and nationalist Kurds.
So far, ISIS has not been as important to Turkey as Assad and the Kurds.
But the ISIS-fabricated Turkish terror attack could change this dynamic.
Russia and Iran also pursue their own regional interests through proxy wars and support for quasi-military operations.
But both countries have indicated their willingness to cooperate with the US to combat ISIS, and they can also collaborate on other issues.
So far, the United States has remained indifferent because its focus has been on overthrowing Assad.
The US foreign policy establishment condemned Russian President Putin for shielding Assad, while Russia condemned the US for attempting to overthrow Assad.
These complaints appear to be contradictory, but they are not.
The United States and its allies' attempt to overthrow Assad violates the UN Charter, while Russia's support for Assad aligns with the charter-recognized right of self-defense of the Syrian people.
Admittedly, Assad is a dictator, but the United Nations Charter does not grant any country the authority to choose which dictator to overthrow.
The persistent presence of ISIS highlights three major strategic flaws in US foreign policy, as well as one fatal tactical flaw.
Firstly, neo-conservatism's demand for achieving American hegemony through toppling regimes not only displays an ignorant bloodthirstiness; it is also the hubris of classic imperialism.
Wherever the United States has tried this, it has always failed.
Syria and Libya are the latest examples.
Secondly, the CIA has for a long time funded and trained Sunni jihadist fighters through secret operations financed via Saudi Arabia.
Conversely, these jihadists gave rise to ISIS, which was the direct (though perhaps unintended) consequence of the same policy pursued by the Central Intelligence Agency and its Saudi collaborators.
Third, the perception of Iran and Russia as intractable enemies for the United States to the extent that they are has largely been a self-fulfilling outdated prophesy.
It is possible to reframe the relationship between the two countries.
Fourth, at the tactical level, the United States has failed to win the dual war against both Assad and ISIS.
Whenever Assad is weakened, Sunni jihadists, including ISIS and al-Nusrah Front, fill the vacuum.
If the United States, Russia, Saudi Arabia, and Iran provided air cover and logistics support, Assad and his Iraqi allies could defeat ISIS.
Indeed, Assad will continue to wield power; indeed, Russia will remain Syria's ally; indeed, Iran will gain influence there.
Terrorist attacks undoubtedly will continue, perhaps for some time still under the ISIS banner; but the organization will be expelled from its bases of operations in Syria and Iraq.
This result not only can eradicate ISIS from the Middle Eastern soil but also lay the groundwork for more comprehensively easing regional tensions.
The United States and Russia could start reversing the new Cold War by jointly combating jihadists and terrorism.
(Alliance commitments to avoid admitting Ukraine or escalating ballistic missile defenses in Eastern Europe could also help.)
There are other benefits as well.
Taking a cooperative approach to combating ISIS will give Saudi Arabia and Turkey reasons and opportunities to seek new pragmatic arrangements with Iran.
The security of Israel could be strengthened by enabling Iran to build cooperative economic and geo-political relationships with the West, thereby increasing the likelihood of a lasting peace agreement between Israel and Palestine.
The rise of ISIS is a manifestation of the strategic flaws of the West—particularly the United States—currently.
The West can defeat ISIS.
The question is whether the United States will undertake a strategic reassessment to achieve this goal.
